obfuscation: Equally important, Dogs take in order to her; and that 's of course sign, little things-- one can always tell, yet something very attractive about her-- what, fine build of wife, and myself shall get hold of her for parish job, and ah, excellent-- excellent; do, wonder if her husband shoots, yet she seems quite-er-- quite---- Quite!
original: Dogs take to her. That's a sure sign. Little things--one can always tell. Something very attractive about her--what! Fine build of woman. I shall get hold of her for parish work. Ah! Excellent--excellent! Do! Wonder if her husband shoots? She seems quite-er--quite----   Quite!

obfuscation: Altogether charming one of nicest faces I ever 've seen, and oh; doctor-- have you; is it----, and right as rain, and she held him like an angel-- he just licked her and never made sound, poor honey; and can I---- Better leave 'em a minute, and she 's mopping ' 'im off.
original: Altogether charming; one of the nicest faces I ever saw. Oh! Doctor--have you? is it----? Right as rain! She held him like an angel--he just licked her, and never made a sound. Poor darling! Can I----        Better leave 'em a minute. She's moppin' 'im off.

obfuscation: On this occasion, Wonderful clever hands, myself say-- who is she, who, and well-- there you have me, and all myself know is she 's first-rate nurse-- been helping ' me with case of Ditch Lane, and nice woman too-- thorough good sort; quite an acquisition here; h 'm!
original: Wonderful clever hands! I say--who is she? Who? Well--there you have me! All I know is she's a first-rate nurse--been helpin' me with a case in Ditch Lane. Nice woman, too--thorough good sort! Quite an acquisition here. H'm!

obfuscation: Excuse me hurrying ' off-- very late; good-bye Rector, yet good-bye Lady all, and good-bye; as h 'm, and i suppose we ought to be bit careful, and beg pardon sir, and is little dog all right; and yes.
original: Excuse me hurryin' off--very late. Good-bye, Rector. Good-bye, Lady Ella. Good-bye! H'm! I suppose we ought to be a bit careful. Beg pardon, sir. Is the little dog all right? Yes.

obfuscation: been ' you 've missed your train m 'm shall myself hang in there and take you 'ome again, no; and cert'nly m 'm; and oh paris-- what 's name of the people here, challenge 's name I have driven 'em in my lady; and challenge; and sounds like a hound.
original: Seein' you've missed your train, m'm, shall I wait, and take you 'ome again? No. Cert'nly, m'm. Oh, Jarvis--what's the name of the people here? Challenger's the name I've driven 'em in, my lady. Challenger? Sounds like a hound.

obfuscation: What 's he such as; and wears a soft 'at mister, and h 'm; and ah; very nice gentleman very nice 'am; yet 'Elped me with my former mare when she 'ad the 'ighsteria last week-- could not 'a ' been kinder if they would 'a ' been angels from 'eaven.
original: What's he like? Wears a soft 'at, sir. H'm! Ah! Very nice gentleman, very nice lady. 'Elped me with my old mare when she 'ad the 'ighsteria last week--couldn't 'a' been kinder if they'd 'a' been angels from 'eaven.

obfuscation: Wonderful fond o ' dumb animals the two of 'em; myself do not pay no attention to gossip myself, as gossip; and what gossip; and did myself make use of term peter 'm, yet you will excuse me myself 'm of course, as there 's still speak where there 's newcomers, i takes people as myself finds 'em.
original: Wonderful fond o' dumb animals, the two of 'em. I don't pay no attention to gossip, meself. Gossip? What gossip? Did I make use of the word, m'm? You'll excuse me, I'm sure. There's always talk where there's newcomers. I takes people as I finds 'em.
